# What is an ISO? How is it different from Normal folders?


- An iso is basically a digital exact replica of a disc or dvd. Basically- it's sturctured in the same way, it is an EXACT image of that dvd/disc. (You're basically not only copying the files but recreating the WHOLE entire disc itself)

## What is flashing?

- Flashing is basically copying the entire dvd exactly as it is onto a pendrive or something.

## What is EFI (Extensible Firmware Interface)?

- EFI is a kind of library/sorting mechanism that stores all bootloaders availabe from different OS.

## What is UEFI (Unified Extensible Firmware Interface)?

- UEFI reads information inside EFI and boots one of the available bootloaders.
- UEFI has a priority order and chooses the bootloader with highest priority to boot in. IT DOES NOT ask you which OS you want to boot in everytime.

## What is a Bootloader?

- A bootloader in simple words- is a program that runs the OS. (Or more accurately starts the OS).

## What is a filesystem?

- A filesystem is the way how an OS stores its files. (Basically rules for how files are supposed to be stored).
  - Windows commonly use NTFS.
  - Linux uses ext4
  - pendrives commonly use exFAT (so that they are readable for linux, windows and macs)
